The terms oscillation and friction occur in high AC field frequency via particle interactions with adjunct particles. Oscillation of nanoparticles in the hydrogel beads can cause friction in the fluid and between the aligned particles [110]. From this perspective, and also principle of magnetization, the microsphere could be a weaken outfit of non-interacting magnetic momentum, while without an external magnetic field, the momentum is arbitrarily oriented, and therefore there is not any net magnetization. The existence of magnetic field (external) tends arranging magnetic moments in order to create magnetization in bulk, where temperature has a direct effect. In high field strength, all magnetic particles ultimately align their moments in the same direction of the magnetic field, and consequently, the magnetization saturation occurs [111]. By turning off the field, the bulk magnetization starts to reduce. Magnetic dipoles can be reoriented via; a) Brownian motions, and b) Néel relaxation [112]. In polymer beads, generally, Brownian motion is restricted due to the trapping of the active domains by polymer chains. Magnetic behavior in case of superparamagnetic materials can be followed by Langevin function, as Eq.3 [111]; M = ϕmMSL(ξ) = ϕmMS (cothξ-1/ξ) (3). In this equation, ϕ
                        m and L(ξ) are volume fraction, and Langevin function, respectively. The later can be calculated by Eq.4; ξ = mH/kT (4). Here, m, H, k, and T are magnetic momentum, external magnetic field, Boltzmann constant, and temperature, respectively. Based on the equations described above, there is not any hysteresis in the magnetization field since M a function of H. In the same vein, the magnetization is directly proportional to the saturation magnetization and concentration of magnetically active domains. In our previous works (Figs. 8 and 9

                        ) [113,114], we reported the application of magnetic hydrogel beads as magnetic drug carriers, and the effect of some factors such as AFM frequency magnitude on drug release. In this research, caffeine (a green precursor) are used for fabrication of Cox-Fey-Oz nanoparticles and used in a pH-sensitive magnetic alginate bead for drug delivery. Therefore, the hydrogel beads can be effectively utilized in controlled-drug release by applying an alternating magnetic field. The presence of magnetic domains can control the drug carrier profile by offering a magnetic power. Sustainability (such as biocompatibility, biodegradability, etc) of the domains (here nanoparticles) as well as beads demonstrated no cytotoxic effect after 24 and 48 h.
